# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: temporal-antialiasing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] In the field of 3D computer graphics, **deferred shading** is a screen-space shading technique that is performed on a second rendering pass, after the vertex and pixel shaders are rendered.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] It was first suggested by Michael Deering in 1988.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] On the first pass of a deferred shader, only data that is required for shading computation is gathered.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Positions, normals, and materials for each surface are rendered into the geometry buffer (G-buffer) using "render to texture".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] After this, a pixel shader computes the direct and indirect lighting at each pixel using the information of the texture buffers in screen space.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Screen space directional occlusion can be made part of the deferred shading pipeline to give directionality to shadows and interreflections.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] The primary advantage of deferred shading is the decoupling of scene geometry from lighting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Only one geometry pass is required, and each light is only computed for those pixels that it actually affects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] This gives the ability to render many lights in a scene without a significant performance hit.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] There are some other advantages claimed for the approach.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] These include simpler management of complex lighting resources, ease of managing other complex shader resources, and the simplification of the software rendering pipeline.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] One key disadvantage of deferred rendering is the inability to handle transparency within the algorithm, although this problem is a generic one in Z-buffered scenes and it tends to be handled by delaying and sorting the rendering of transparent portions of the scene.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Depth peeling can be used to achieve order-independent transparency in deferred rendering, but at the cost of additional batches and g-buffer size.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Modern hardware, supporting DirectX 10 and later, is often capable of performing batches fast enough to maintain interactive frame rates.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] When order-independent transparency is desired (commonly for consumer applications) deferred shading is no less effective than forward shading using the same technique.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Another serious disadvantage is the difficulty with using multiple materials.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] It's possible to use many different materials, but it requires more data to be stored in the G-buffer, which is already quite large and takes up a large amount of the memory bandwidth.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] One more disadvantage is that, due to separating the lighting stage from the geometric stage, hardware anti-aliasing does not produce correct results anymore since interpolated subsamples would result in nonsensical position, normal, and tangent attributes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Although it is not an edge-smoothing technique, temporal anti-aliasing (used in *Halo: Reach and Unreal Engine*) can also help give edges a smoother appearance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] DirectX 10 introduced features allowing shaders to access individual samples in multi-sampled render targets (and depth buffers in version 10.1), giving users of this API access to hardware anti-aliasing in deferred shading.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] These features also allow them to correctly apply HDR luminance mapping to anti-aliased edges, where in earlier versions of the API any benefit of anti-aliasing may have been lost.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Use of the technique has increased in video games because of the control it enables in terms of using a large amount of dynamic lights and reducing the complexity of required shader instructions.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] In comparison to deferred lighting, this technique is not very popular due to high memory size and bandwidth requirements, especially on seventh generation consoles where graphic memory size and bandwidth are limited and often bottlenecks.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] The idea of deferred shading was originally introduced by Michael Deering and his colleagues in a paper published in 1988 titled *The triangle processor and normal vector shader: a VLSI system for high performance graphics*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Although the paper never uses the word "deferred", a key concept is introduced; each pixel is shaded only once after depth resolution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Deferred shading as we know it today, using G-buffers, was introduced in a paper by Saito and Takahashi in 1990, although they too do not use the word "deferred".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] The first deferred shaded video game was *Shrek*, an Xbox launch title shipped in 2001.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] Around 2004, implementations on commodity graphics hardware started to appear.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/deferred-shading] The technique later gained popularity for applications such as video games, finally becoming mainstream around 2008 to 2010.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] In computer vision and image processing, **motion estimation** is the process of determining *motion vectors* that describe the transformation from one 2D image to another; usually from adjacent frames in a video sequence.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] It is an ill-posed problem as the motion happens in three dimensions (3D) but the images are a projection of the 3D scene onto a 2D plane.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] The motion vectors may relate to the whole image (*global motion estimation*) or specific parts, such as rectangular blocks, arbitrary shaped patches or even per pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] The motion vectors may be represented by a translational model or many other models that can approximate the motion of a real video camera, such as rotation and translation in all three dimensions and zoom.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] More often than not, the term motion estimation and the term *optical flow* are used interchangeably.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] It is also related in concept to *image registration* and *stereo correspondence*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] In fact all of these terms refer to the process of finding corresponding points between two images or video frames.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] The points that correspond to each other in two views (images or frames) of a real scene or object are "usually" the same point in that scene or on that object.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Before we do motion estimation, we must define our measurement of correspondence, i.e., the matching metric, which is a measurement of how similar two image points are.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] There is no right or wrong here; the choice of matching metric is usually related to what the final estimated motion is used for as well as the optimisation strategy in the estimation process.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Each *motion vector* is used to represent a *macroblock* in a picture based on the position of this macroblock (or a similar one) in another picture, called the reference picture.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] The methods for finding motion vectors can be categorised into pixel based methods ("direct") and feature based methods ("indirect").
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] A famous debate resulted in two papers from the opposing factions being produced to try to establish a conclusion.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Statistical functions that have been successfully used include RANSAC.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] It can be argued that almost all methods require some kind of definition of the matching criteria.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] The difference is only whether you summarise over a local image region first and then compare the summarisation (such as feature based methods), or you compare each pixel first (such as squaring the difference) and then summarise over a local image region (block base motion and filter based motion).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] An emerging type of matching criteria summarises a local image region first for every pixel location (through some feature transform such as Laplacian transform), compares each summarised pixel and summarises over a local image region again.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Some matching criteria have the ability to exclude points that do not actually correspond to each other albeit producing a good matching score, others do not have this ability, but they are still matching criteria.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Affine motion estimation is a technique used in computer vision and image processing to estimate the motion between two images or frames.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] It assumes that the motion can be modeled as an affine transformation (translation + rotation + zooming), which is a linear transformation followed by a translation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Applying the motion vectors to an image to synthesize the transformation to the next image is called motion compensation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] It is most easily applied to discrete cosine transform (DCT) based video coding standards, because the coding is performed in blocks.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] As a way of exploiting temporal redundancy, motion estimation and compensation are key parts of video compression.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] Almost all video coding standards use block-based motion estimation and compensation such as the MPEG series including the most recent HEVC.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/motion-estimation] In simultaneous localization and mapping, a 3D model of a scene is reconstructed using images from a moving camera.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital signal processing, **spatial anti-aliasing** is a technique for minimizing the distortion artifacts (aliasing) when representing a high-resolution image at a lower resolution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is used in digital photography, computer graphics, digital audio, and many other applications.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing means removing signal components that have a higher frequency than is able to be properly resolved by the recording (or sampling) device.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This removal is done before (re)sampling at a lower resolution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] When sampling is performed without removing this part of the signal, it causes undesirable artifacts such as black-and-white noise.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In signal acquisition and audio, anti-aliasing is often done using an analog anti-aliasing filter to remove the out-of-band component of the input signal prior to sampling with an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital photography, optical anti-aliasing filters made of birefringent materials smooth the signal in the spatial optical domain.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The anti-aliasing filter essentially blurs the image slightly in order to reduce the resolution to or below that achievable by the digital sensor (the larger the pixel pitch, the lower the achievable resolution at the sensor level).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, anti-aliasing improves the appearance of "jagged" polygon edges, or "jaggies", so they are smoothed out on the screen.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, it incurs a performance cost for the graphics card and uses more video memory.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The level of anti-aliasing determines how smooth polygon edges are (and how much video memory it consumes).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Near the top of an image with a receding checker-board pattern, the image is difficult to recognise and often not considered aesthetically pleasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In contrast, when anti-aliased the checker-board near the top blends into grey, which is usually the desired effect when the resolution is insufficient to show the detail.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Even near the bottom of the image, the edges appear much smoother in the anti-aliased image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Multiple methods exist, including the sinc filter, which is considered a better anti-aliasing algorithm.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] When magnified, it can be seen how anti-aliasing interpolates the brightness of the pixels at the boundaries to produce grey pixels since the space is occupied by both black and white tiles.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] These help make the sinc filter antialiased image appear much smoother than the original.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In a simple diamond image, anti-aliasing blends the boundary pixels; this reduces the aesthetically jarring effect of the sharp, step-like boundaries that appear in the aliased graphic.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is often applied in rendering text on a computer screen, to suggest smooth contours that better emulate the appearance of text produced by conventional ink-and-paper printing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Particularly with fonts displayed on typical LCD screens, it is common to use subpixel rendering techniques like ClearType.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sub-pixel rendering requires special colour-balanced anti-aliasing filters to turn what would be severe colour distortion into barely-noticeable colour fringes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Equivalent results can be had by making individual sub-pixels addressable as if they were full pixels, and supplying a hardware-based anti-aliasing filter as is done in the OLPC XO-1 laptop's display controller.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Pixel geometry affects all of this, whether the anti-aliasing and sub-pixel addressing are done in software or hardware.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most basic approach to anti-aliasing a pixel is determining what percentage of the pixel is occupied by a given region in the vector graphic - in this case a pixel-sized square, possibly transposed over several pixels - and using that percentage as the colour.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This method is generally best suited for simple graphics, such as basic lines or curves, and applications that would otherwise have to convert absolute coordinates to pixel-constrained coordinates, such as 3D graphics.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is a fairly fast function, but it is relatively low-quality, and gets slower as the complexity of the shape increases.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] For purposes requiring very high-quality graphics or very complex vector shapes, this will probably not be the best approach.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Note: The `plot_antialiased_point` routine above cannot blindly set the colour value to the percent calculated.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] It must **add** the new value to the existing value at that location up to a maximum of 1.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Otherwise, the brightness of each pixel will be equal to the darkest value calculated in time for that location which produces a very bad result.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] For example, if one point sets a brightness level of 0.90 for a given pixel and another point calculated later barely touches that pixel and has a brightness of 0.05, the final value set for that pixel should be 0.95, not 0.05.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In this approach, the ideal image is regarded as a *signal*.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The image displayed on the screen is taken as samples, at each (*x,y*) pixel position, of a filtered version of the signal.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Ideally, one would understand how the human brain would process the original signal, and provide an on-screen image that will yield the most similar response by the brain.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most widely accepted analytic tool for such problems is the Fourier transform; this decomposes a signal into basis functions of different frequencies, known as frequency components, and gives us the amplitude of each frequency component in the signal.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] where *j* and *k* are arbitrary non-negative integers.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are also frequency components involving the sine functions in one or both dimensions, but for the purpose of this discussion, the cosine will suffice.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The numbers *j* and *k* together are the *frequency* of the component: *j* is the frequency in the *x* direction, and *k* is the frequency in the *y* direction.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Current knowledge of human visual perception is not sufficient, in general, to say what approach will look best.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The previous discussion assumes that the rectangular mesh sampling is the dominant part of the problem.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The filter usually considered optimal is not rotationally symmetrical, as shown in this first figure; this is because the data is sampled on a square lattice, not using a continuous image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This sampling pattern is the justification for doing signal processing along each axis, as it is traditionally done on one dimensional data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Lanczos resampling is based on convolution of the data with a discrete representation of the sinc function.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] If the resolution is not limited by the rectangular sampling rate of either the source or target image, then one should ideally use rotationally symmetrical filter or interpolation functions, as though the data were a two dimensional function of continuous x and y.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The sinc function of the radius has too long a tail to make a good filter (it is not even square-integrable).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] A more appropriate analog to the one-dimensional sinc is the two-dimensional Airy disc amplitude, the 2D Fourier transform of a circular region in 2D frequency space, as opposed to a square region.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] One might consider a Gaussian plus enough of its second derivative to flatten the top (in the frequency domain) or sharpen it up (in the spatial domain), as shown.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Functions based on the Gaussian function are natural choices, because convolution with a Gaussian gives another Gaussian whether applied to x and y or to the radius.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Similarly to wavelets, another of its properties is that it is halfway between being localized in the configuration (x and y) and in the spectral (j and k) representation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an interpolation function, a Gaussian alone seems too spread out to preserve the maximum possible detail, and thus the second derivative is added.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an example, when printing a photographic negative with plentiful processing capability and on a printer with a hexagonal pattern, there is no reason to use sinc function interpolation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Such interpolation would treat diagonal lines differently from horizontal and vertical lines, which is like a weak form of aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are only a handful of primitives used at the lowest level in a real-time rendering engine (either software or hardware accelerated).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] These include "points", "lines" and "triangles".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one is to draw such a primitive in white against a black background, it is possible to design such a primitive to have fuzzy edges, achieving some sort of anti-aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, this approach has difficulty dealing with adjacent primitives (such as triangles that share an edge).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] To approximate the uniform averaging algorithm, one may use an extra buffer for sub-pixel data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The initial (and least memory-hungry) approach used 16 extra bits per pixel, in a 4 × 4 grid.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one renders the primitives in a careful order, such as front-to-back, it is possible to create a reasonable image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Since this requires that the primitives be in some order, and hence interacts poorly with an application programming interface such as OpenGL, the latest methods simply have two or more full sub-pixels per pixel, including full color information for each sub-pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] There is also an approach specialised for texture mapping called mipmapping, which works by creating lower resolution, pre-filtered versions of the texture map.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] When rendering the image, the appropriate-resolution mipmap is chosen and hence the texture pixels (texels) are already filtered when they arrive on the screen.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Mipmapping is generally combined with various forms of texture filtering in order to improve the final result.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because fractals have unlimited detail and no noise other than arithmetic round-off error, they illustrate aliasing more clearly than do photographs or other measured data.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The escape times, which are converted to colours at the exact centres of the pixels, go to infinity at the border of the set, so colours from centres near borders are unpredictable, due to aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This example has edges in about half of its pixels, so it shows much aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The first image is uploaded at its original sampling rate.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] (Since most modern software anti-aliases, one may have to download the full-size version to see all of the aliasing.) The second image is calculated at five times the sampling rate and down-sampled with anti-aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Assuming that one would really like something like the average colour over each pixel, this one is getting closer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is clearly more orderly than the first.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In order to properly compare these images, viewing them at full-scale is necessary.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] It happens that, in this case, there is additional information that can be used.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] By re-calculating with a "distance estimator" algorithm, points were identified that are very close to the edge of the set, so that unusually fine detail is aliased in from the rapidly changing escape times near the edge of the set.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The colours derived from these calculated points have been identified as unusually unrepresentative of their pixels.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The set changes more rapidly there, so a single point sample is less representative of the whole pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Those points were replaced, in the third image, by interpolating the points around them.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This reduces the noisiness of the image but has the side effect of brightening the colours.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] So this image is not exactly the same that would be obtained with an even larger set of calculated points.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] To show what was discarded, the rejected points, blended into a grey background, are shown in the fourth image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Finally, "Budding Turbines" is so regular that systematic (Moiré) aliasing can clearly be seen near the main "turbine axis" when it is downsized by taking the nearest pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The aliasing in the first image appears random because it comes from all levels of detail, below the pixel size.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] When the lower level aliasing is suppressed, to make the third image and then that is down-sampled once more, without anti-aliasing, to make the fifth image, the order on the scale of the third image appears as systematic aliasing in the fifth image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Super sampling anti-aliasing (SSAA), also called full-scene anti-aliasing (FSAA), is used to avoid aliasing (or "jaggies") on full-screen images.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] SSAA was the first type of anti-aliasing available with early video cards.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] But due to its tremendous computational cost and the advent of multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA) support on GPUs, it is no longer widely used in real time applications.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] MSAA provides somewhat lower graphic quality, but also tremendous savings in computational power.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The resulting image of SSAA may seem softer, and should also appear more realistic.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, while useful for photo-like images, a simple anti-aliasing approach (such as super-sampling and then averaging) may actually worsen the appearance of some types of line art or diagrams (making the image appear fuzzy), especially where most lines are horizontal or vertical.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In these cases, a prior grid-fitting step may be useful (see hinting).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] In general, super-sampling is a technique of collecting data points at a greater resolution (usually by a power of two) than the final data resolution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] These data points are then combined (down-sampled) to the desired resolution, often just by a simple average.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The combined data points have less visible aliasing artifacts (or moiré patterns).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Full-scene anti-aliasing by super-sampling usually means that each full frame is rendered at double (2x) or quadruple (4x) the display resolution, and then down-sampled to match the display resolution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Thus, a 2x FSAA would render 4 super-sampled pixels for each single pixel of each frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Rendering at larger resolutions will produce better results; however, more processor power is needed, which can degrade performance and frame rate.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sometimes FSAA is implemented in hardware in such a way that a graphical application is unaware the images are being super-sampled and then down-sampled before being displayed.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] A graphics rendering system creates an image based on objects constructed of polygonal primitives; the aliasing effects in the image can be reduced by applying an anti-aliasing scheme only to the areas of the image representing silhouette edges of the objects.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The silhouette edges are anti-aliased by creating anti-aliasing primitives which vary in opacity.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] These anti-aliasing primitives are joined to the silhouetted edges, and create a region in the image where the objects appear to blend into the background.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] The method has some important advantages over classical methods based on the accumulation buffer since it generates full-scene anti-aliasing in only two passes and does not require the use of additional memory required by the accumulation buffer.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Object-based anti-aliasing was first developed at Silicon Graphics for their Indy workstation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Digital images are usually stored in a gamma-compressed format, but most optical anti-aliasing filters are linear.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] So to down-sample an image in a way that would match optical blurring, one should first convert it to a linear format, then apply the anti-aliasing filter, and finally convert it back to a gamma compressed format.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Using linear arithmetic on a gamma-compressed image results in values which are slightly different from the ideal filter.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] This error is larger when dealing with high contrast areas, causing high contrast areas to become dimmer: bright details (such as a cat's whiskers) become visually thinner, and dark details (such as tree branches) become thicker, relative to the optically anti-aliased image.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is individually distorted, meaning outlines become unsmooth after anti-aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because the conversion to and from a linear format greatly slows down the process, and because the differences are usually subtle, most image editing software, including Final Cut Pro and Adobe Photoshop, process images in the gamma-compressed domain.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/spatial-anti-aliasing] Most modern GPUs support storing textures in memory in sRGB format, and can perform transformation to linear space and back transparently, with essentially no loss in performance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Aliasing is manifested in the case of 2D images as moiré pattern and pixelated edges, colloquially known as "jaggies".
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Common signal processing and image processing knowledge suggests that to achieve perfect elimination of aliasing, proper spatial sampling at the Nyquist rate (or higher) after applying a 2D Anti-aliasing filter is required.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] As this approach would require a forward and inverse fourier transformation, computationally less demanding approximations like supersampling were developed to avoid domain switches by staying in the spatial domain ("image domain").
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Supersampling is computationally expensive because it requires much greater video card memory and memory bandwidth, since the amount of buffer used is several times larger.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] A way around this problem is to use a technique known as **adaptive supersampling**, where only pixels at the edges of objects are supersampled.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Initially only a few samples are taken within each pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] If these values are very similar, only these samples are used to determine the color.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The result of this method is that a higher number of samples are calculated only where necessary, thus improving performance.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] When taking samples within a pixel, the sample positions have to be determined in some way.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Although the number of ways in which this can be done is infinite, there are a few ways which are commonly used.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The pixel is split into several sub-pixels, and a sample is taken from the center of each.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Although, due to the regular nature of sampling, aliasing can still occur if a low number of sub-pixels is used.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Also known as stochastic sampling, it avoids the regularity of grid supersampling.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] However, due to the irregularity of the pattern, samples end up being unnecessary in some areas of the pixel and lacking in others.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The Poisson disk sampling algorithm places the samples randomly, but then checks that any two are not too close.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The end result is an even but random distribution of samples.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The naive "dart throwing" algorithm is extremely slow for large data sets, which once limited its applications for real-time rendering.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] However, many fast algorithms now exist to generate Poisson disk noise, even those with variable density.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] The Delone set provides a mathematical description of such sampling.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] A modification of the grid algorithm to approximate the Poisson disk.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] A pixel is split into several sub-pixels, but a sample is not taken from the center of each, but from a random point within the sub-pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] Congregation can still occur, but to a lesser degree.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] A 2×2 grid layout is used but the sample pattern is rotated to avoid samples aligning on the horizontal or vertical axis, greatly improving antialiasing quality for the most commonly encountered cases.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/supersampling] For an optimal pattern, the rotation angle is arctan (⁠1/2⁠) (about 26.6°) and the square is stretched by a factor of ⁠√5/2⁠, making it also a 4-queens solution.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The modern definition of TAA is a spatial anti-aliasing technique for real-time computer graphics that reuses information from previously rendered frames to remove aliasing, such as jaggies, from the current frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The term *temporal anti-aliasing* is somewhat of a misnomer, and this technique is formally referred to as *temporally-amortized supersampling.* It is also known as TXAA (an implementation by Nvidia) or *Temporal Super-Sampling Anti-Aliasing* (TSSAA).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] This method can achieve results comparable to supersampling, at a small fraction of the computational cost, but produces soft images and can cause ghosting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA popularized in video games in the 2010s, with two early examples being Halo: Reach and Crysis 2, and is now the most common form of spatial anti-aliasing in real-time rendering and game engines.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is sampled at a slightly different position each frame, which is achieved by adding a 2D offset to each frame, a "jitter" that shifts the image by a fraction of the size of a pixel, horizontally and vertically.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The jitter changes each frame, following a pattern (such as a Halton sequence) so that every point in the image is sampled evenly over time.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Old frames are blended into the current frame, accumulating historical rendering data, approaching the result of supersampling over time.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Changes to the scene—such as moving objects, camera motion, or changes in lighting—often mean that the history for any given pixel may be somewhere else on screen, be invalid, or may not exist at all.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Failure to account for these changes results in ghosting.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] To account for movement, velocity vectors are maintained in the G-buffer, allowing the location of each pixel in the previous frame to be calculated.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The pixel at that location in the previous frame is accumulated into a history buffer, at its new location.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Accurate velocities are required to prevent smearing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Often, the historical data for a pixel will become invalid due to changes in occlusion, such as the pixel having recently become visible after being blocked by an object last frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] This causes ghosting unless it is detected: One method is to compare the depth of the historical position to the depth values in the current pixel's neighborhood.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Color can also be useful for validating the history of a pixel, since a sudden change in color can indicate new lighting conditions or an incorrect pixel velocity.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] A drawback of TAA is that it does not work well with transparent objects, particles, or reflections, because they can produce incorrect velocity vectors.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] In the case of transparency, this is because only one velocity vector can typically be stored per pixel.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Dithering can be used to simulate opacity, a technique known as *screen-door transparency*, which works with TAA and is smoothed out over time by it.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Ghosting and blurriness are two disadvantages specific to TAA, though both can be significantly reduced with proper implementation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA requires more engine- and game-specific tuning than other anti-aliasing methods to achieve acceptable results; poorly-tuned implementations can severely exacerbate TAA's issues in some situations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Brute force supersampling (rendering at a higher resolution and downsampling), which is considered a gold standard for spatial anti-aliasing, is very costly compared to TAA, which can produce comparable results in many situations.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA), which was previously the most common real-time spatial anti-aliasing method, does not work well with deferred shading, which is needed for a number of common rendering techniques.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Several post-processing anti-aliasing methods were developed to overcome this limitation, such as fast approximate anti-aliasing (FXAA), and morphological anti-aliasing (MLAA).
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] These methods can have poor temporal stability, such as causing flickering artifacts.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA generally reduces aliasing better than these methods, is more temporally stable, and still works with deferred shading.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Deep learning super sampling (DLSS), developed by Nvidia, operates on similar principles to TAA.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Like TAA, it uses information from past frames to produce the current frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Unlike TAA, DLSS does not sample every pixel in every frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Instead, it samples different pixels in different frames and uses pixels sampled in past frames to fill in the unsampled pixels in the current frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] DLSS uses machine learning to combine samples in the current frame and past frames, and it can be thought of as an advanced TAA implementation.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The traditional definition of TAA is the removal of temporal aliasing.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] A photograph collects light over a period of time, called an exposure.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] This can result in moving objects exhibiting motion blur, which is sometimes a desirable effect.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, images are often rendered at a single instant in time, ignoring the effects of motion, for convenience.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] This results in temporal aliasing: moving objects can appear to jump or flash between frames as their position changes.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] This effect can be mitigated, but not eliminated, by using a higher refresh rate display, and increasing the frame rate to match the refresh rate.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Another approach, analogous to spatial supersampling, is to simulate motion blur by rendering many instants in time, integrating them into each frame.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Aliasing is a result of the sampling theorem of signal processing: To avoid it, a signal must be sampled at a rate at least twice the highest frequency present in the signal.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] An example of temporal aliasing is the wagon-wheel effect, where spinning objects can appear to move slowly, stop, or reverse.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Temporal aliasing can also affect film and video.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] The shutter behavior of the sampling system (the camera) strongly influences aliasing, because the window function of the exposure (its shape over time) determines how well bandlimited the image signal is before sampling.
[src:temporal-antialiasing/temporal-anti-aliasing] Different window functions can be chosen to reduce temporal aliasing.
